Brain Stroke Prediction - ML Pipeline¶

Description & Utility

This ML pipeline predicts wether a client is at risk of having a stroke.

It is useful for hospitals to know whom may require more care. This pipeline could potentially save lives by alerting healthcare professionals to intervene and prevent any possible episodes.

I gathered my data from the following kaggle dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/zzettrkalpakbal/full-filled-brain-stroke-dataset

In this notebook, I will begin by loading then splitting the dataset to test and train. I will then plot a few chats to visualize the data. Furthermore, I will conduct Data Preprocessing and Feature engineering to prep for the predicition and handle imbalance by creating dummy variables. Afterwards, I will use two classification methods to classify the dataset and using the best method, I will finally predict the chances of having a brain stroke.

3) VISUALIZING THE DATASET¶

To visualize the dataset, I must plot various charts:

  • Using the matplotlib library I was able to plot pie chart and histograms for each column, for both categorical and numerical columns

  • Using seaborn I was able to plot a scattered plot to visualize how the age column may effect the outcomes of the other numerical columns, such as heart disease.

However, before plotting charts, I decided to create two lists to seperate categorical and numerical columns.

After creating two empty lists, one for categorical and one for numerical, I set a for loop that goes through all given columns in the dataset, checks what type of data is stored in the column, and depending on the results, appends the column to its righteous list.

In [6]:
cat = []
num = []

for col in df.columns:
    if df[col].dtype == 'object':
        cat.append(col)
    else:
        num.append(col)
        
print('Categorical columns: ', cat)
print('\nNumerical columns: ', num)

Categorical columns:  ['gender', 'ever_married', 'work_type', 'Residence_type', 'smoking_status']

Numerical columns:  ['age', 'hypertension', 'heart_disease', 'avg_glucose_level', 'bmi', 'stroke']

Pie Chart - Categorical Columns¶

To create a pie chart for every categorical column in the dataset individually, I set a for loop to go through all the elements in the categorical list created above, and plot a pie chart for each one of them

  • Using "figsize" i was able to manipulate the sizing of the charts.
In [7]:
for cat_element in cat:

Histogram - Numerical Columns¶

To create a histogram for every numerical column in the dataset individually, I set a for loop to go through all the elements in the numerical list created above, and plot a histogram for each one of them

  • Using the "bins" i was able to manipulate the size of the bars in the charts.
  • I also set each numerical value on the x-axis with the method "set_xlabel()"

To do so for every numerical column, I created a for loop that will iterate len(num) amount of times, while starting at the second index to avoid the age column.

8) FINAL DISCUSSION & INSIGHTS¶

  • Feature Importance:

As we can see, age plays a big role in increasing the stroke probabilities. The older a person is, the more likeley they are to have medical issues.

  • Data Imbalance:

I used SMOTE to boost the proportion of minority samples in the dataset, which may enhance the model's performance.

  • Model selection:

I did tested two Classification models: Decision Tree and SVC

Because decision tree is easier to read and can offer insights into the variables that are most crucial in forecasting possible strokes, I picked it over SVC.

In addition to handling non-linear relationships well, decision trees are less sensitive to outliers than SVC. Moreover, decision trees can accommodate a greater number of characteristics without overfitting and are less computationally expensive.

  • Model performance:

Accuracy: The model's accuracy rating is 0.765, or 76.5%. This indicates that 76.5% of the samples in the test set were properly categorised by the model.

Precision: The model's precision rating is [0.91666667, 0.4]. This indicates that the model's accuracy is 91.7% for the second class and 40% for the first class. The percentage of accurate positive predictions compared to all positive forecasts is known as precision.

Recall: The model's recall score is [0.78571429, 0.66666667]. This indicates that the model's recall for the first class is 78.6% and for the second class is 66.7%. Recall quantifies the percentage of correct predictions made from all real positive samples.

F1-Score: The model has an F1-score of [0.84615385, 0.5]. This indicates that the model's F1-score for the first class is 84.6% and for the second class is 50%. When the classes are unbalanced, a reasonable statistic to employ is the F1-score, which is a weighted harmonic mean of precision and recall.

I opted for accuracy above precision because misclassifying a non-stroke case as a stroke case has considerably more severe repercussions than failing to detect a true stroke case.

By using this method, the model is ensured to accurately identify as many potential stroke cases as possible, helping to prevent delayed or ineffective treatment, which could have detrimental effects on the patient's life.

  • Business impact:

I believe such ML pipelines are crucial for the healthcare industry. Investing in a precise and accurate pipeline that could predict potential health risks could evade life or death situations and save many lives.
